-- 
S. African Stocks: Anglo American, Murray & Roberts, Pick n Pay

-- B y   R o b e r t   B r a n d
-- 
2011-04-18T16:14:13Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-18/s-african-stocks-anglo-american-murray-roberts-pick-n-pay.html
The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index
had its biggest one-day decline in more than a month, falling
839.03, or 2.6 percent, to 31,388.63 at the 5 p.m. close in
Johannesburg. Six stocks fell for every one that rose.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AAL)  , the diversified miner that
makes up 11 percent of the index, dropped 16 rand, or 4.6
percent, to 333 rand, the lowest closing price since Dec. 15, as
commodity prices tumbled after the U.S.’s ratings outlook was
revised to negative from stable by  Standard & Poor’s .  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s largest mining
company, fell the most in two weeks, losing 6.94 rand, or 2.5
percent, to 273.16 rand.  ArcelorMittal South Africa Ltd. (ACL)  , a unit of the world’s biggest steelmaker, declined 4.58
rand, or 5.2 percent, to 84.17 rand.  Murray & Roberts Holdings Ltd. (MUR)  , a construction
company, slipped 1.17 rand, or 4.4 percent, to 25.28 rand, its
lowest close since March 17, after saying it may incur further
antitrust penalties.  Pick n Pay Stores Ltd. (PIK)  ,  South Africa ’s second-
biggest grocer, slumped 2.40 rand, or 5.4 percent, to 41.80
rand, the lowest closing price since June 9. The company said it
expects another six months of “difficult” trading conditions
after second-half profit fell 29 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
